<h1>From Robert Dinwiddie</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">[Williamsburg] June 20th 1757</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Yr Letter by Express, I received last Night,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> &amp; I am sorry for the Intelligence it brings of such a No. of French &amp; Indians marching from Fort Du Quesne, and its more than probable their Design is agst Fort Cumberland, and am sorry that Garrison is in so poor a Condition for Defence, &amp; I really fear it is in the Enemys Hands before this can reach You. If so they probably will proceed to fort Loudoun. in Order to reinforce You, Ive orderd One Third of the Militia of the following Counties to march immediately to fort Loudoun, Vizt Frederick, Fairfax, Prince William, Culpepper, Orange, Stafford, which, I hope together will amot to 1000 Men<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0002-ptr">2</a>I doubt not Colo. Stanwix will march his regulars where the greatest Danger is or where the Enemy may be, that when the Men are all collected in a Body, I doubt not will be able to repell the force of the Enemy, &amp; You are to follow such Orders Colo. Stanwix may send Yo. from Time to Time, witht any regard to any Orders Yo. may have received from me,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> &amp; as probably he may order Men to join him, I cd not prevail with the Assembly to allow the Militia to be
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-04-02-pb-0244">[244]</span>
marchd out of this Dominion, therefore if he Orders Men, Yo. must supply him from yr regimt, &amp; either yourself, or some other good Officer to rema[in] at fort Loudoun wth the Militia to protect that Garrison, but at present Im of Opinion that Colo. Stanwix will chuse to come to fort Loudoun as most centrical, &amp; from thence form his Dispositions, I know not where he is, when Yo. write him pray send my ComplimentsI sent for the Councell this Morning, &amp; they agree with me to what yr Councell of Warr advisd &amp; therefore advise You to send for the Men from the different small forts to be ready on a Call at fort Loudoun<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0004-ptr">4</a>I cant conceive the Enemy can be so numerous as Mr Levingston mentions, when I consider the Report of the Officer that is a Prisoner, &amp; Sergeant Fent assurd me there were not 150 French, besides Indians at fort Du Quesne;<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0005" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> however as they march wth a Train of Artillery, its probable theyve Men enough to invest &amp; take fort Cumberland. I am of Opinion they must want Provisions, if possible to prevent their having a Suply will be a great Point. Mr Boyd brings 10,000, which I believe is all the Money now coined; Im sorry they have no small Bills, The Treasurer says in a fortnight he will have a Qty printedIve sent 240 to Mr Atkin to pay for the Scalps, brot in by the Swallows PartyAs to the Peoples Demand for Indians they shall be pd when produced;<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0006" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0006-ptr">6</a> Money is not ready; Colo. Stephen left an Accott of 48 for that Service chiefly for Liquors, which is pd this Day, &amp; any other hereafter will be pd with proper VouchersIm sorry fort Loudoun is not finishd it has been a long Time in hand, but now I expect that by double Diligence Youll be able soon to compleat it, &amp; Yo. see the Necessity. Let me know, if Yo. possibly can, the No. of the Enemy, &amp; what Artillery they may have; Im under great Uneasiness on your present Situation, Yet I doubt not wth the Regulars, Provincials &amp; Militia, Yo. will be able to stand your ground, &amp; more so as I dare say Colo. Stanwix will exert himself on this OccasionIve orderd Winchester &amp; Fredericksburg for the Rendesvouz of the Drafts from the Country Militia. I therefore order You to send 8 or 10 of yr Subaltern Officers, to receive those that may come to Fredericksburg, &amp; I think it will be necessary to send em immediately<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0007" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0007-ptr">7</a>Im so hurried that I cannt write Yo. a particular Answer to each Paragraph of yr Letters, but I think the above are the most sustantial Points. Im in great
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-04-02-pb-0245">[245]</span>
Pain for Capt. Spotswood, his being safe returnd will give me much JoyI cannt determine on forming the two additional Companies to yr Regimt, till I see how many Men will be raised, as Ive some Doubts on the Mode prescribd for raising them, that I shall be glad if they amo. sufficient to compleat the 8 Companies now in the Country. Or do I think of the 3 Companies of Rangers till that is finishd, as I thought it wd interferr wth the Drafts<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0008" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0008-ptr">8</a>I must now leave off, wishing to hear a good Accott of yr troublesome Neighbours. I rema. with Respect Sir yr h. S.</p>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Virginia Historical Society, Richmond ]">ViHi</span>: Dinwiddie Papers.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0129" class="document">GW to Dinwiddie, 16 June 1757</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0165" class="document">GW to Henry Lee and Culpeper County Lieutenant, 25 June 1757</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0166" class="document">to Orange County Lieutenant, Henry Fitzhugh, and John Spotswood, same date</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>See GWs inquiry on this head in <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0115" class="document">his letter to Dinwiddie of 10 June 1757</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>The record of the proceedings of the council 20 June are in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ H. R. McIlwaine et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Executive Journals of the Council of Colonial Virginia&lt;/i&gt;. 6 vols. Richmond, 192566. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Exec. Journals of Virginia Council</span></span>, 6:5758.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p><a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0127" class="document">GW had enclosed James Livingstons letter of 14 June</a> in <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0129" class="document">his letter to Dinwiddie of 16 June</a>. <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0122" class="document">GW wrote in his second letter of 12 June to Dinwiddie</a> of James Bakers capture of a French officer, but he did not refer to any Report from him. For Joseph Fents escape from Fort Duquesne, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0091" class="document">GW to Dinwiddie, 24 May 1757</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p><a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0122" class="document">GW wrote Dinwiddie 12 June 1757 (second letter)</a> that people were demanding payment of their many indian accompts against the Country and again on 10 July that the people were unhappy with Dinwiddies response. After Dinwiddie complained on 18 July that he did not know what these accounts were, GW on 3 Aug. 1757 gave a full explanation.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>The procedure for enlisting and drafting men for the Virginia Regiment is set out in an act passed in the session of the legislature ending 8 June 1757 (7 <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ William Waller Hening, ed. &lt;i&gt;The Statutes at Large; Being a Collection of All the Laws of Virginia, from the First Session of the Legislature, in the Year 1619&lt;/i&gt;. 13 vols. 181923. Reprint. Charlottesville, Va., 1969. ]">Hening</span> 6987). See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0107&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-04-02-0107-fn-0002#GEWN-02-04-02-0107-fn-0002" class="document">Dinwiddie to GW, 6 June 1757, n.2</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0008-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0152-fn-0008">8</a>

   <p>Provision for the rangers was included in the act cited in note 7.</p>

</div>
</div>
